title: New trend sees women getting G-SPOT INJECTIONS
text: Share this article Share Cosmetic nurse, Kate Sowden, from the BeautyFULL Cosmetic Medical Clinic in Brisbane, said the procedure has proven popular with all sorts of women. However, she said it is mostly a hit with those over the age of 35. 'It's an all-natural product so there's a very low risk of having any sort of adverse reaction or anything like that,' she said. The procedure involves injecting dermal fillers into the G-Spot after anaesthetic, and promises to 'improve sensitivity where you need it most' (stock photo) Getting a G Shot is 'very comfortable for clients' according to Cosmetic nurse, Kate Sowden, and the results can last up to four months (stock photo) Ms Sowden added that the procedure is 'very comfortable for clients', and the results can last up to four months. On the BeautyFULL website, experts say that after receiving the G Shot, 87 per cent of women reported enhanced sexual arousal and gratification. In further good news, the G Shot is often touted as a lunchtime injection, as it takes just 30 minutes to complete. Experts say that after receiving the G Shot, 87 per cent of women reported enhanced sexual arousal and gratification (stock photo) Having your G-Spot amplified doesn't come cheap, however. In Australia, the injection retails at around AUD $900, while in the UK it can cost as much as GBP £800. The Gräfenberg spot, or G-Spot, was originally discovered by a German doctor in the 1950s.
